05269nam a22010935i 9780520911802DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t19921992cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209118027 a10.1525/97805209118022doi  a(DE-B1597)518676  a(OCoLC)44958210  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGN662b.W45 1992eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.4209951 aWeiner, Annette B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInalienable Possessions :bThe Paradox of Keeping-While Giving /cAnnette B. Weiner. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInalienable Possessions tests anthropology's traditional assumptions about kinship, economics, power, and gender in an exciting challenge to accepted theories of reciprocity and marriage exchange. Focusing on Oceania societies from Polynesia to Papua New Guinea and including Australian Aborigine groups, Annette Weiner investigates the category of possessions that must not be given or, if they are circulated, must return finally to the giver. Reciprocity, she says, is only the superficial aspect of exchange, which overlays much more politically powerful strategies of "keeping-while-giving."The idea of keeping-while-giving places women at the heart of the political process, however much that process may vary in different societies, for women possess a wealth of their own that gives them power. Power is intimately involved in cultural reproduction, and Weiner describes the location of power in each society, showing how the degree of control over the production and distribution of cloth wealth coincides with women's rank and the development of hierarchy in the community. Other inalienable possessions, whether material objects, landed property, ancestral myths, or sacred knowledge, bestow social identity and rank as well. Calling attention to their presence in Western history, Weiner points out that her formulations are not limited to Oceania. The paradox of keeping-while-giving is a concept certain to influence future developments in ethnography and the theoretical study of gender and exchange.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAnthropologie économiquexMéthodologiexOcéaniexOzeanienxOceania. 0aCeremonial exchangexOceania. 0aCeremonial exchangezOceania. 0aEconomic anthropologyxMethodologyxOceania. 0aEconomic anthropologyzOceaniaxMethodology. 0aFeminist anthropologyxOceania. 0aFeminist anthropologyzOceania. 0aFemmesxConditions socialesxOcéanie. 0aFemmesxConditions économiquesxOcéanie. 0aWomenxEconomic conditionsxOceania. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxOceania. 0aWomenzOceaniaxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzOceaniaxSocial conditions. 0aÉchange cérémonielxOcéanie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaboriginal.  aacademic.  aancestry.  aanthropology.  aaustralia.  acultural anthropology.  aculture.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  afeminism.  afeminist.  afinance.  agender issues.  agender studies.  agift giving.  agiving gifts.  aidentity.  ainternational.  akinship.  amarriage.  amoney.  aoceania.  apapua new guinea.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apolynesia.  apossessions.  apower.  aproperty.  aresearch.  asacred.  ascholarly.  asocial studies.  awestern history.  awomens issues.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091180240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.